But to understand it rightly, we must consider that a Law may be unjust either by reason of the End, Manner, or some Circum- stance extrinsic to the Law, or by reason of the Matter or Object of the Law itself. It may be the command of an unjust thing, or it may be a thing unjustly commanded. The material or intrinsic injustice of the Law destroys the obligation3 the accidental or extrinsic inJustice does not.

Thus, if a Sovereign should command something not (morally) un· lawfuL or forbid something not (morally) necessary3 doing this without good reason, or for the purpose of gain, or even through tyrannous caprice, or evil passion3 the command would be unJust in him, but the subJect would be bound to obey. The Prince sinsin issuing such a command3 but the Subject sins in disobeying it.
